What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 84853 loans with 27 features, including ProsperScore, DebtToIncomeRatio, LoanOriginalAmount BorrowerAPR BorrowerRate, Term and many others.

Most variables are numeric and categorical in nature.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

As a consultant to Prosper Limited Company, I am interested in figuring out which factors the firm should put more emphasison when lending money to their clients and the general prospects that will enhace profitability of the firm such as lending funds to borrowers who have a low risk of default.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

For the analysis to be successful, several features have to be explored in-depth so as to come up with a trustworthy report.

More emphasis will be layed in the following features which prove to be of more use in this analysis:

I will focus on features that the firm should put consideration in when determining if a client is worth being given a loan. The fearures of interest are: Occupation, Employment status, Collateral(is the borrower a home owner), Debt-to-income ratio, Original loan amount, Loan status and Income range.

Univariate Exploration¶

I will investigate features that I am mostly interested in using for my analysis.

Debt To Income Ratio¶

In [29]:
# Plot DebtToIncomeRatio
binsize = 0.05
bins = np.arange(0, data_select['DebtToIncomeRatio'].max()+binsize, binsize)
plt.figure(figsize=[6,6])
plt.hist(data = data_select, x = 'DebtToIncomeRatio', bins = bins, color='darkgreen')
plt.xlabel('Debt to Income Ratio')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('A Distribution of Debt To Income Ratio');

Notes¶

A Debt To Income Ratio compares how much an individual owes in each month in comparison to income they get. A high debt to income ratio signifies that an individual uses a large portion of their income to pay debt. On the other hand, a low debt to income ratio demonstrates that the individual is using a relatively small amount of their income to pay debt.

From the above histogram, it is seen that a vast majority of the borrowers have a Debt To Income ratio of around 30%.

    '''
    doctring: creating a function that creates a histogram of the data

Notes¶

The distribution of BorrowerRate appears to be normally distributed except that there is a peak at around 0.33. A borrower is more likely to be charged high rates (between 12%-20%) with the highest rate being 33% from loans they obtain from Prosper.

n_loans=data_select['LoanStatus'].value_counts().sum()
status_count=data_select['LoanStatus'].value_counts()
status_order=status_count.index

sns.countplot(data=data_select, x='LoanStatus', color="darkgreen", order=status_order);

# get the current tick locations and labels
locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=45) 

# loop through each pair of locations and labels
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
    count = status_count[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_loans)

    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
    plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha = 'center', color='darkgreen')

Establishing the relationship between Loan Amount and Borrower Rate.¶

In [47]:
#Create a new column which return 1 for good status of payment('Current','Completed','FinalPaymentInProgress') 
# and 0 if there is an issue (defaulted,past due, charged-off payments)

recommend_loan=['Current','Completed','FinalPaymentInProgress']
def loanstatus_val(doc):
    for i in recommend_loan:
        if i in doc:
            return 1
    return 0
data_select["loan_status"] = data_select.LoanStatus.apply(lambda x: loanstatus_val(x))

Notes¶

Rates charged by Prosper are based on whether the borrower owns a home or not and their employement status. Owning a home serves as a collateral to the loan taken. Individuals without homes are charged a higher rate because they do not have homes to be used as collateral.

Employment is also a factor considered when charging rates on loans. Because unemployed individuals lack regular income to service their loan, they are charged higher rates as compared to their peers as they have a higher risk of defaulting.

Employed people attract lower rates charged on their loans.
